and it as a self-conscious artefact, circulating between friends and strangers and across multiple genres in ways that both make and break social ties.Key FeaturesDraws together different emphases on the intellectual, literary and social uses of letter writing Provides students and researchers with a means to situate letters in their wider theoretical and historical contextsMethodologically expansive, intellectually interrogative chapters based on original research by leading academicsOffers new insights into the lives and careers of Louisa May Alcott, Charles Brockden Brown, Emily Dickinson, Frederick Douglass, Margaret Fuller, Henry James, Thomas Jefferson, Abraham Lincoln, Herman Melville, Harriet Beecher Stowe, and Edgar Allan Poe, among many others"  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAmerican lettersxHistory and criticismxUnited States. 0aAmerican lettersxHistory and criticism. 0aLetter writingxHistoryx19th centuryxUnited States. 0aLetter writingzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aAllen, Judith A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnesko, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnard, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernier, Celeste-Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBray, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDunlavy Valenti, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFagg, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFloyd, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFolsom, Ed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator